    <action datetime="1995-06-27T21:26:00-04:00">
      <text>Rules Committee Resolution H. Res. 173 Reported to House. Rule provides for consideration of H.J. Res. 79 with 1 hour of general debate. Previous question shall be considered as ordered without intervening motions except motion to recommit with or without instructions. The motion to recommit may include instructions only if offered by the Minority Leader or his designee. If the motion to recommit includes instructions, the motion shall be debatable for one hour, equally divided.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T12:18:00-04:00">
      <text>Rule H. Res. 173 passed House.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T12:19:00-04:00">
      <text>Considered under the provisions of rule H. Res. 173.</text>
      <reference ref="CR H6415-6446" label="consideration"/>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T12:19:00-04:00">
      <text>Rule provides for consideration of H.J. Res. 79 with 1 hour of general debate. Previous question shall be considered as ordered without intervening motions except motion to recommit with or without instructions. The motion to recommit may include instructions only if offered by the Minority Leader or his designee. If the motion to recommit includes instructions, the motion shall be debatable for one hour, equally divided.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T12:19:00-04:00">
      <text>DEBATE - Pursuant to the provisions of H. Res. 173, the House proceeded with one hour of debate.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T13:58:00-04:00">
      <text>The previous question was ordered pursuant to the rule.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T13:58:00-04:00">
      <text>Mr. Bryant (TX) moved to recommit with instructions to Judiciary.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T13:59:00-04:00">
      <text>DEBATE - Pursuant to the provisions of H. Res. 173, the House proceeded with one hour of debate on the motion to recommit with instructions that the Committee report the bill back to the House with an amendment in the nature of a substitute which would give the Congress and the states the power to prohibit burning, trampling, soiling, or rendering the flag of the United States. The amendment would also direct the Congress to develop a legal definition of what a flag is and to prescribe procedures for the proper disposal of worn or damaged flags.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T15:11:00-04:00">
      <text>The previous question on the motion to recommit with instructions was ordered without objection.</text>
    </action>
    <action datetime="1995-06-28T15:32:00-04:00">
      <text>On motion to recommit with instructions Failed by the Yeas and Nays: 63 - 369 (Roll no. 430).</text>
      <reference ref="CR H6445" label="consideration"/>
    </action>
